  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/vad-hemolysis-decision-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/fda-cdrh-vv-review-panel",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment is accepted based on the following structured evidence review. (1) Operating envelope and applicability: The COU declares an explicit bounded operating envelope (flow 3–7 L/min, speed 2400–3600 RPM, hematocrit 35–45%) with a documented applicability constraint excluding extrapolation, transient conditions, and cavitation. This explicit bounding reduces effective model risk. (2) Validation coverage: All five validation operating points lie within the declared envelope and span its full extent, including both corners and the centre. Validation is dense and directly relevant. (3) Factor assessment: All 13 credibility factors are assessed with achievedLevel >= requiredLevel. Key factors — output comparison (achieved 4 vs. required 3), test conditions (achieved 4 vs. required 3), and validation relevance (achieved 4 vs. required 3) — exceed requirements. No factor gaps remain. (4) Uncertainty quantification: Monte Carlo UQ (2000 samples) performed at all five operating points; total NIH uncertainty ±10–12% at 95% CI. Maximum relative error between CFD and experiment is 4.5%, well within the UQ bounds. (5) Provenance: Complete provenance chain from foundational experimental data through CFD runs to validation results is documented and traceable. All ValidationResult objects have comparedAgainst, prov:wasGeneratedBy, and hasUncertaintyQuantification links. (6) The bounded applicability constraint is correctly recognised as a credibility-enhancing feature, not a limitation. The package is clean and all requirements for acceptance are met.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
